Base image with OMNeT (for all three platforms) and specific INET-{platform}-{mode} version to testbuild ANSA with Travis-CI.

hooks/build:
Docker hub build hook. Builds image and tags it with IMAGE_NAME generated by hooks/env

hooks/env:
Parse DOCKER_TAG (when executed on docker hub) or the latest git tag from current repository
to get OMNeT++ and INET version.
Expected DOCKER_TAG syntax: <omnet-version>-<inet-version>-<platform>-<mode> for example 5.4.1-v4.0.0-linux-release.

The last git tag expected syntax: <repository>-<omnet-version>-<inet-version>-<platform>-<mode> for example travis-ansainet-base-5.4.1-v4.0.0-linux-release.
Optionally it can contain "-rc<number>" or "-pre<number>" suffix.

Default values are used if the parsing fails.

hooks/gen_builds:
Generate all six images {linux, windows, macosx} x {release, debug}.
Parses the last tag on current repository and calls hooks/build to build the image.

hooks/push_images:
Push locally built images to the repository (if you don't want to wait for docker hub build).
Accept single parameter <omnet-version>-<inet-version>.


Manual build:
1. Build single image.
Set DOCKER_TAG environment variable and run
export DOCKER_TAG="5.4.1-v4.0.0-linux-release"
./hooks/build

2. Build all six images.
./hooks/gen_builds

3. Push images to docker hub

./hooks/push_builds.sh 5.4.1-v4.0.0




Why don't all scripts follow the same argument passing convention?
Well, that would be too easy, wouldn't it?
